'''Tobihata Hachimangu''' (飛幡八幡宮) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] located in [[:en:Tobata-ku, Kitakyūshū|Tobata Ward, Kitakyushu]], [[:en:Kitakyushu|Kitakyushu]], [[:en:Fukuoka Prefecture|Fukuoka Prefecture]]. It was formerly Ranked as a {{ill|Prefectural Shrine|ja|県社|lt=Ken-sha|1=Modern_system_of_ranked_Shinto_shrines#Metropolitan_and_Prefectural_Shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prefectural Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 近代社格制度}} and is currently listed as a [[:en:Beppyo shrine|Beppyo Shrine]] by the [[:en:Association of Shinto Shrines|Association of Shinto Shrines]].

== Deities ==
The shrine enshrines [[:en:Hachiman|Hachiman]] ([[:en:Empress Jingū|Empress Jingū]] and [[:en:Emperor Ōjin|Emperor Ōjin]]), {{ill|Himegami|ja|比売大神|lt=Hime-no-Ōkami|1=Himegami|3=比売神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Himegami|13=User:Immanuelle/Himegami|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 比売神}}, {{ill|Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|須佐之男命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to スサノオ}}, and [[:en:Dōsojin|Dōsojin]].

== History ==
In the Kenkyū period (1190-1199), {{ill|Utsunomiya Shigeie|ja|宇都宮重業|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utsunomiya Shigeie|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, ancestor of the {{ill|Utsunomiya clan|ja|宇都宮氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utsunomiya clan|qq=}} ({{ill|Aso clan|ja|麻生氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aso clan|qq=}}), brought the Hachiman deity from his hometown of Utsunomiya and enshrined it in Miyata Mountain in Edamitsu Village, which was the {{ill|Kimon|ja|鬼門|1=Kimon|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kimon|qq=}} (northeast) of {{ill|Hanao Castle|ja|花尾城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hanao Castle|qq=}}. Later, the shrine was moved to Tobata Village and became the guardian deity of Tobata and Nakahara Villages. During the Edo period, it was designated a prayer site by the [[:en:Kuroda clan|Kuroda clan]]. In 1920, it was relocated to its current site in Asano. In 1931, it was designated a Prefectural Shrine. In 1995, the shrine's name was changed from "Tobata Hachiman Shrine" to "Tobihata Hachimangu."

== festivals ==
The [[:en:Tobata Gion Yamagasa festival|Tobata Gion Yamakasa]] festival, held on the fourth weekend of July, is a major event at the shrine and at {{ill|Sugawara Shrine (Tobata Ward, Kitakyushu)|ja|菅原神社 (北九州市戸畑区)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sugawara Shrine (Tobata Ward, Kitakyushu)|qq=}} and Nakahara Hachiman Shrine in the ward. It is designated as an {{ill|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|重要無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|qq=}} of Japan. According to the {{ill|Chikuzen Kuni Zoku Fudoki|ja|筑前国続風土記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chikuzen Kuni Zoku Fudoki|qq=}}, the festival began in Kyōwa 2 (1802) when an epidemic broke out in Tobata Village. After praying for healing at the shrine to {{ill|Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|須佐之男命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to スサノオ}}, the epidemic ceased, and the festival was started the following year.

